@rdblue I took a quick look at the PR, and added some more debug statements, and it seems that the failure is related to some timeouts waiting for the spark context to start:

This is what I am seeing on the messages received from the kernel
```

{'buffers': [],

  'content': {'data': {'text/plain': 'Waiting for a Spark session to start...'},

              'metadata': {},

              'source': 'user'},

  'header': {'date': '2017-05-30T00:54:07.076455',

             'msg_id': 'e74f827d-5694-463e-b71a-8d9b53b80a96',

             'msg_type': 'display_data',

             'session': '704f5820-eb0d-48e7-b088-f2ee0c2889f8',

             'username': 'root',

             'version': '5.0'},

  'metadata': {'timestamp': '1496105642479'},

  'msg_id': 'e74f827d-5694-463e-b71a-8d9b53b80a96',

  'msg_type': 'display_data',

  'parent_header': {'msg_id': 'e4b5bb9d-683e-4a3d-ad17-d0e75f202c5a',

                    'msg_type': 'execute_request',

                    'session': '44d3ab80-6bf8-45ff-a233-d03e507a6db4',

                    'username': 'username',

                    'version': '5.0'}},
```

And it seems it's failing in Kernel.scala

```
override def sparkSession: SparkSession = {
    // the first call to getOrCreate may create a session and take a long time,
    // so this starts a future to get the session. if it take longer than 100 ms,
    // then print a message to the user that Spark is starting.
    import scala.concurrent.ExecutionContext.Implicits.global
    val sessionFuture = Future {
      SparkSession.builder.config(defaultSparkConf).getOrCreate
    }

    try {
      Await.result(sessionFuture, Duration(100, TimeUnit.MILLISECONDS))
    } catch {
      case timeout: TimeoutException =>
        // getting the session is taking a long time, so assume that Spark is
        // starting and print a message
        display.content(MIMEType.PlainText, "Waiting for a Spark session to start...")
        Await.result(sessionFuture, Duration.Inf)
    }
  }
```

@lresende -- I understand Spark's Yarn code ([spark/deploy/yarn/ApplicationMaster](https://github.com/apache/spark/blob/3d4d11a80fe8953d48d8bfac2ce112e37d38dc90/resource-managers/yarn/src/main/scala/org/apache/spark/deploy/yarn/ApplicationMaster.scala#L402)) is waiting for a `SparkContext` to be initialized before registering the Yarn application as `RUNNING`.

However, I am not convinced that it is necessary for the Toree kernel application to be in `RUNNING` state in order to connect to the kernel. Some applications may want to connect to the Toree kernel regardless of Yarn application status and only trigger the SC initialization once a notebook cell execution actually requires it.

So, in order to not entirely "defeat" the purpose of the "lazy initialization" of the `SparkContext` ([TOREE-390](https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/TOREE-390): commit 5cfbc83) for Toree kernels running in Yarn cluster mode, would it be feasible to introduce a parameter or option to either "force" SC initialization or allow for "lazy" initialization? In keeping with the spirit of this PR, the default may then be to "force" SC init.
